üîê Key Concepts Reviewed

Authentication & Access Control

3FA (Three-Factor Authentication):

Something you know (password)

Something you have (token/smart card)

Something you are (biometrics)

802.1X: Network access control using EAP between supplicant, authenticator, and authentication server

Prevents unauthorized devices from accessing LAN/WLAN

Network & Infrastructure Resilience

Load Balancing: Distributes traffic across multiple servers to improve performance, availability, and fault tolerance

RAID: Combines multiple physical disks into one logical unit for redundancy, reliability, and performance

Jump Servers: Intermediate systems used to securely access internal resources

Threats & Attacks

Brute Force Attacks: Repeated attempts to guess passwords or encryption keys

Buffer Overflow: Exploiting excess data written to memory buffers

On-Path (MITM) Attacks: Intercepting or modifying traffic between two endpoints

Endpoint & Network Security

EDR: Monitors endpoints to detect and respond to malicious activity

IDS: Monitors traffic patterns and detects anomalies

SASE: Cloud-based framework combining networking and security services

Application & Software Security

Input Validation: Prevents injection attacks by sanitizing user input

Application Allow Lists: Only approved applications are allowed to run

Firmware: Embedded software in hardware devices; outdated firmware can introduce vulnerabilities

Code Signing: Verifies software authenticity and integrity

Risk Mitigation

Compensating Controls: Alternative controls used when primary controls aren‚Äôt feasible

Cold Sites: Backup data centers without active hardware; longest recovery time

